{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17491318","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17491318"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T05:42:14+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T05:42:14+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"911"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"911","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/911"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.05,0.07,0.35,0.41,0.12]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"911"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"67935"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"911","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/911"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"911"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53400"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"31"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"251"},{"type":"tags","id":"1139"},{"type":"tags","id":"1151"},{"type":"tags","id":"1261"},{"type":"tags","id":"2436"},{"type":"tags","id":"2589"},{"type":"tags","id":"3817"},{"type":"tags","id":"3893"},{"type":"tags","id":"9598"},{"type":"tags","id":"9644"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"4229"},{"type":"contributions","id":"9095"},{"type":"contributions","id":"18138"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"67935","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/67935"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 74-year-old man presents with a one month history of increasing tiredness. He has never had these symptoms before and is otherwise in good health. The physical examination is unremarkable and his standard laboratory investigations are all normal apart from an iron-deficiency anaemia of 118 g/L (128-175). An endoscopy and colonoscopy are performed. The only abnormality found is a 1 cm area of mucosal irregularity in the distal stomach. This is biopsied and two of the tissue samples show adenocarcinoma, which appears to be confined to the mucosa. A CT of the chest, abdomen and pelvis is unremarkable.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following investigations is likely to be of the most value in further staging the disease?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Carcinoembryonic antigen","MRI abdomen","Endoscopic ultrasound and mucosal resection","PET scan","Laparoscopy"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EAfter endoscopy and biopsy, assessment and staging of gastric cancer will starting with imaging. This will involve either CT or MRI of the chest, abdomen and pelvis - and not just the abdomen alone. If no evidence of T3 or T4 disease is found, then attention can be given to a more detailed local assessment.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn this case the endoscopic examination suggests early (T0 or T1) gastric cancer. On the assumption that appropriate imaging has excluded metastatic or distant nodal disease, more attention can be paid to the primary tumour and the assessment of regional lymph nodes. An accurate assessment of the degree of mucosal, submucosal or lamina propria involvement can be made by \u003Cstrong\u003Eendoscopic ultrasound combined with endoscopic mucosal resection\u003C/strong\u003E. This will be able to assess the depth of tumour invasion and the status of adjacent lymph nodes, with an accurate T and N staging. On the assumption that this is an early gastric cancer, the incidence of lymph node involvement or metastatic spread with this stage of disease is very low and probably in the range of 1 - 2%.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIf distant metastases were suspected, then a \u003Cstrong\u003EPET\u003C/strong\u003E \u003Cstrong\u003Escan\u003C/strong\u003E may be helpful in detecting metastases. The PET scan is usually combined with a low resolution non-contrast CT. Only about 50% of gastric cancers are PET-avid and particularly those in the proximal stomach.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECarcinoembryonic antigen\u003C/strong\u003E is increased in perhaps 50% of cases of gastric cancer, but it is not a staging tool.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA staging \u003Cstrong\u003Elaparoscopy\u003C/strong\u003E could be considered in patients where resection of the primary tumour is contemplated. This approach could be used to exclude peritoneal deposits - which are not always detected on CT imaging.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAs an alternative to endoscopic ultrasound, this area could be resected endoscopically and this might give an accurate histological assessment as to the degree of infiltration of tumour into the deeper layers.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIf \u003Cstrong\u003EMRI\u003C/strong\u003E scanning was to be performed, it would not be confined to the abdomen - gastric cancer can spread up the lymphatic system and a scan including the chest and neck would be required.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Endoscopic ultrasound has a key role in the staging of early gastric cancers."],"references":["Van Cutsem E, Sagaert X, Topal B, et al. Gastric Cancer. Lancet. 2016 Nov 26;388(10060):2654-2664. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/27156933/","Cho JW, Choi SC, Jang JY, et al. Lymph Node Metastases in Esophageal Carcinoma: An Endoscopist\u0027s View. Clin Endosc. 2014 47; 6: 523\u201329. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/25505718/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53400"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"911"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"5